    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-03-04T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-03-04T06:00:00-05:00" n="663"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d663">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">493.11 Shelton, Dr. A. L.: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-03-04T19:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 4, 1922—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 6—10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>28. Following telegram has been received from consul [at] Chungking: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Following telegram has been received from American missionary at Batang:
                            ‘Robbers killed Doctor A. L. Shelton<note n="25" xml:id="d663fn25"
                                >American missionary of the Tibetan Christian Mission, Batang,
                                Szechuan Province.</note> near Batang. I have asked local government
                            to investigate at once. Department’s registration number 16539.’”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Telegram dated 2d, signed Hardy<note n="26" xml:id="d663fn26">Dr. William M.
                        Hardy, colleague of Dr. Shelton.</note> [apparent omission] left Yunnan
                    Province states Doctor Shelton killed February 17th at Sasweisan. Have informed
                    Foreign Office today requesting it to take immediately all possible measures to
                    ascertain circumstances of this reported crime and to apprehend and bring to
                    trial guilty parties. Shall reserve representations particularly on the basis of
                    Department [<hi rend="italic">diplomatic corps’?</hi>] note to Foreign Office of
                    August 30th, 1921,<note n="27" xml:id="d663fn27">See despatch no. 45, Sept. 29,
                        1921, from the Minister in China, <ref target="frus1921v01#pg_516">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1921, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 516</ref>.</note> regarding possible
                    failure of provincial authorities to <pb facs="0981" n="861" xml:id="pg_861"/>
                    afford proper protection to foreign residents until facts and delinquencies of
                    local officials are more clearly ascertained. British consul, Yunnan;
                    representative, Andersen, Meyer, Yunnan; and American consulate, Chungking, have
                    been requested to furnish all possible assistance. Will keep Department
                    advised.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
